---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---

<BaseLayout title="About" description="More about Gert-Willem van Gompel.">
	<main class="about-page">
		<h1 class="about-title">Gert-Willem</h1>
		<article class="about-content">

			<p>For most of my career I designed buildings. Residential projects — from first client meeting through permit applications and site supervision. I liked the work, and I was drawn to the technical side of it: matching what a client wanted with what regulations and physics would actually allow, finding solutions for details that had to work on every level simultaneously.</p>

			<p>What frustrated me was how much potential the tools had, and how little of it got used. Colleagues drawing a rectangle for each wall instead of using the built-in wall object. BIM workflows that could have automated half the documentation, sitting unused. At the scale of the offices I worked in, nobody had made the time to set it up properly — so eventually I did.</p>

			<p>That pattern kept repeating — and gradually expanding. What started as optimising my own project workflow shifted toward rethinking how the office itself operated. Sales process, incoming prospects, the administrative overhead around it all. Technically that was someone else's job — my boss handled sales, a part-time secretary came in once a week. By the time the automations were running, she was down to a few hours. This was before anyone was dramatically screaming about AI replacing jobs. I did it without AI — mostly just repetitive copy-paste work that turned out to be trivially automatable with the right tools.</p>

			<p>In the summer of 2025 I quit my job and took the entrance exam for 42 Belgium — four weeks, intensive, ended with an 84% on the final Piscine exam. I got in! I started the Common Core in October. A few weeks later, 42 changed the curriculum: Python was added, and there was more focus on AI. Good timing.</p>

			<p>Seven months later: C, Python, Rust, LLMs, a multiplayer TCP server, an autonomous code repair agent. Peer review that forces you to actually understand what you wrote. No teachers, no lectures, no hiding behind vague answers.</p>

			<p>I'm now looking for a role where I can keep building. Where the work is technically interesting and the problems are real.</p>

			<p>Outside of work: motorcycles, travel, an ongoing interest in how things are built — physically, digitally, systemically.</p>

			<p class="status-line">
				Currently looking for work in software and ML engineering.
			</p>
		</article>
	</main>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
	.about-page {
		width: 100%;
		padding: calc(var(--nav-h) + 4em) 1em 6em;
	}

	.about-title {
		font-family: var(--font-display);
		font-size: clamp(2.5rem, 6vw, 4rem);
		font-weight: 700;
		color: rgb(var(--black));
		margin: 0 0 3rem;
		text-transform: uppercase;
		letter-spacing: 0.02em;
		line-height: 1.05;
		text-align: center;
	}

	.about-content {
		width: 680px;
		max-width: calc(100% - 2em);
		margin: 0 auto;
		font-size: 1rem;
		line-height: 1.75;
		color: rgb(var(--gray-dark));
	}

	.about-content p {
		margin: 0 0 1.75em;
	}

	.status-line {
		margin-top: 3em !important;
		padding-top: 2em;
		border-top: 1px solid rgb(var(--gray-light));
		font-size: 0.9rem;
		font-weight: 300;
		color: rgb(var(--gray));
		letter-spacing: 0.03em;
	}
</style>
